Y0usef

Target IP: 192.168.195.138

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage is displayed for this application. Digging through the source-code for this webpage does not show anything useful.


Doing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.195.138/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt shows the interesting result above.


There is an interesting directory called /administration. Browsing to this directory shows the webpage above.


Using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.195.138/administration/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-small.txt -x php,html,txt, I discovered a few other directories. But performing directory search against these directories did not result in anything helpful.



I intercepted the GET request to /administration/ and added a new header field X-Forwarded-For: localhost and obtained the login webpage above! It seems the host is vulnerable to header manipulation.



By using the default credentials admin:admin, I gained access to the website. There is an interesting page called Upload file as shown above. Looks like I can upload file using this feature. I tried to upload a .php file and it did not work!

Exploitation



After some enumeration, I found out it is possible to bypass the filter in place by changing the Content-Type to image/gif. I used the PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script. And I get the confirmation the file has been uploaded to /files/1689282746shell.phtml. I will start a listener on 8443 and visit the uploaded file.


And now I have a foothold on the machine. I visited http://192.168.195.138/administration/upload/files/1689282746shell.phtml to obtain the reverse shell connection on port 8443.

Privilege Escalation


Running uname -a shows the host's kernel version is 3.13.0-24-generic and it is vulnerable to overlayfs local privilege escalation. I downloaded this exploit on my machine, and transferred it to the target machine.


After compiling and executing the exploit, I gained a root shell.
